    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-08-30T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-08-30T10:00:00-05:00" n="203"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d203">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/281: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-08-30T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 30, 1929—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 30—3:22 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>160. Reference Embassy’s 159, August 30, 3 p.m. The Russian Embassy here has just
                    delivered the answer to the Chinese proposal. It is a general acquiescence, but
                    subject to conditions. Among them the chief one is that the Russians have the
                    right to appoint again the former manager, rather than be limited to appoint a
                    new manager, which is stipulated in the Chinese note. However, the Russian
                    representative orally explained that, if the Chinese insisted upon a new <pb
                        facs="0452" n="308" xml:id="pg_308"/> manager being appointed and would
                    themselves appoint a new president of the railway board, the Russian Government
                    might consent.</p>
                <p>The Russians propose that the negotiations begin not later than September 15 at
                    Moscow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
